---
name: chester-util-codereview
description: >
  Code smell review of existing code scoped to a directory, namespace, or path.
  Spawns three parallel agents — Bloaters & Dispensables, Couplers & OO Abusers,
  and Change Preventers (each augmented with mapped SOLID checks) — to identify
  code smells present in the target code. Based on the five smell categories from
  refactoring.guru/refactoring/smells plus SOLID principles distributed across the
  smell agents. Invoke via: "review code in src/", "smell check this directory",
  "code review src/billing", "what smells exist in lib/", "/chester-util-codereview".
---

# Code Review

Analyzes existing code in a scoped directory for code smells. Every finding must cite
real evidence — file paths, line numbers, class/method names, or concrete code patterns.
Speculation without evidence is not a finding.

## Relationship to other review skills

- `chester-plan-smell` is forward-looking — it reviews plans for smells they *would* introduce
- This skill is present-tense — it reviews code that *already exists*

Both use the same smell taxonomy. They do not overlap: one reviews plans, the other reviews code.

## Scope

The user provides a target: a directory path, a namespace, or a glob pattern. Agents
confine their exploration to that scope. Code outside the scope is only relevant when
the scoped code directly depends on it (imports, inheritance, interface contracts).

This constraint matters because without it, agents will wander the entire repo and produce
findings about code the user didn't ask about — wasting time and diluting the report.

## Workflow

### Step 1 — Resolve the scope

Determine what code to review. The user will either:

- Name a directory: `src/billing/`, `lib/auth`
- Name a namespace or module: `billing`, `auth.providers`
- Provide a glob: `**/*Controller.ts`
- Have a contextual reference: "this directory", "the code we just wrote"

If the scope is ambiguous or missing, ask the user to specify. Do not default to the
entire repo — that defeats the purpose of scoped review.

Once resolved, confirm the scope briefly: "Reviewing `src/billing/` for code smells."

Explore the target scope to understand what's there before launching agents. Identify:

- The languages and frameworks in use
- Key files, classes, and modules within the scope
- Approximate size (handful of files vs. large subsystem)
- Entry points and public interfaces

This context goes to each agent so they aren't exploring blind.

### Step 2 — Launch three agents in parallel

Launch all three agents in a single message using the Agent tool. Each agent receives
a scope summary and file listing as the first content, followed by a `---` delimiter,
then agent-specific analysis instructions. Each agent has `subagent_type` "Explore" so
it can read the codebase but cannot modify files.

The scope summary should include:
- The target path/pattern
- Languages and frameworks detected
- Key files and their apparent roles
- Any notable patterns observed during Step 1

---

**Agent 1 — Bloaters & Dispensables**

Prompt the agent with:

> ## Scope
> Target: `<scope-path>`
> Languages: <detected languages>
> Key files:
> <file listing with brief role descriptions>
>
> ---
>
> Review the existing code within the scope above for Bloater and Dispensable code smells. Read the actual source files — do not guess from file names alone.
>
> Bloater smells to look for:
> - Long Method: methods/functions that do too much and should be split
> - Large Class: classes that have taken on too many responsibilities
> - Primitive Obsession: primitives passed around where value objects or named types belong
> - Long Parameter List: methods/functions with too many parameters
> - Data Clumps: groups of related data that travel together without a named type
>
> Dispensable smells to look for:
> - Duplicate Code: repeated logic that exists in multiple places
> - Dead Code: constructs that are never called or reached
> - Lazy Class: classes too thin to justify their existence
> - Speculative Generality: abstraction layers with no current consumer beyond one call site
> - Comments as Crutch: comments explaining logic that should be self-evident from structure
>
> SOLID-mapped smells to also check:
> - Does any class take on more than one reason to change? (SRP as Large Class)
> - Are there fat interfaces that force implementors to depend on methods they don't use? (ISP as Long Parameter List / fat interface bloat)
>
> Rules:
> - Every finding MUST cite a specific file path, line number or range, and the construct involved
> - Read the code. If you cannot find concrete evidence in the source files, drop the finding
> - Classify each finding as Critical (significant structural harm), Serious (real quality
>   cost that will compound over time), or Minor (low-impact)
> - Confine your exploration to `<scope-path>` — only look outside the scope when tracing
>   a direct dependency (import, inheritance, interface)
>
> Output format:
> ## Bloaters & Dispensables Findings
>
> ### Findings
> - **[Critical|Serious|Minor]** | `file:line` | finding | evidence
>   > Optional detail block for complex findings
>
> Omit empty sections. Omit detail blocks unless the finding cannot be understood without them.

---

**Agent 2 — Couplers & OO Abusers**

Prompt the agent with:

> ## Scope
> Target: `<scope-path>`
> Languages: <detected languages>
> Key files:
> <file listing with brief role descriptions>
>
> ---
>
> Review the existing code within the scope above for Coupler and OO Abuser code smells. Read the actual source files — do not guess from file names alone.
>
> Coupler smells to look for:
> - Feature Envy: methods that use another class's data more than their own
> - Inappropriate Intimacy: classes that reach too deeply into each other's internals
> - Message Chains: long call chains (a.B().C().D()) that expose navigation paths
> - Middle Man: classes that do nothing but delegate to another with no added value
>
> OO Abuser smells to look for:
> - Switch Statements: type-based switching where polymorphism belongs
> - Temporary Field: fields that are only meaningful in some execution paths
> - Refused Bequest: subclasses that ignore or override most of what their parent provides
> - Alternative Classes with Different Interfaces: classes that do the same thing under
>   different method names or signatures
>
> SOLID-mapped smells to also check:
> - Does any subclass behave in a way that would break code written against the base class
>   contract? (LSP as Refused Bequest)
> - Do high-level modules depend directly on low-level modules rather than on abstractions?
>   (DIP as Feature Envy / Inappropriate Intimacy)
>
> Rules:
> - Every finding MUST cite a specific file path, line number or range, and the construct involved
> - Read the code. If you cannot find concrete evidence in the source files, drop the finding
> - Classify each finding as Critical, Serious, or Minor
> - Confine your exploration to `<scope-path>` — only look outside the scope when tracing
>   a direct dependency
>
> Output format:
> ## Couplers & OO Abusers Findings
>
> ### Findings
> - **[Critical|Serious|Minor]** | `file:line` | finding | evidence
>   > Optional detail block for complex findings
>
> Omit empty sections. Omit detail blocks unless the finding cannot be understood without them.

---

**Agent 3 — Change Preventers**

Prompt the agent with:

> ## Scope
> Target: `<scope-path>`
> Languages: <detected languages>
> Key files:
> <file listing with brief role descriptions>
>
> ---
>
> Review the existing code within the scope above for Change Preventer code smells — structural decisions that make the code harder to change. Read the actual source files — do not guess from file names alone.
>
> Change Preventer smells to look for:
> - Divergent Change: classes with multiple unrelated responsibilities such that future
>   changes to different concerns all require touching the same class
> - Shotgun Surgery: a single concern distributed across many files such that any change
>   to that concern requires touching all of them
> - Parallel Inheritance Hierarchies: class hierarchies that mirror each other, requiring
>   additions to one whenever you add to the other
>
> SOLID-mapped smells to also check:
> - Does any class hold multiple unrelated responsibilities? (SRP as Divergent Change)
> - Would adding new behavior require modifying existing closed classes rather than extending?
>   (OCP as Shotgun Surgery)
>
> For each smell found, assess the blast radius: roughly how many files would need to change
> if the affected concern were modified?
>
> Rules:
> - Every finding MUST cite specific file paths, line numbers, and constructs as evidence
> - Read the code. If you cannot find concrete evidence in the source files, drop the finding
> - Classify each finding as Critical, Serious, or Minor
> - Confine your exploration to `<scope-path>` — only look outside the scope when tracing
>   a direct dependency
>
> Output format:
> ## Change Preventers Findings
>
> ### Findings
> - **[Critical|Serious|Minor]** | `file:line` | finding | evidence
>   > Optional detail block for complex findings
>
> Omit empty sections. Omit detail blocks unless the finding cannot be understood without them.

---

### Step 3 — Synthesize the smell report

**Structured Thinking gate:** Before merging, use Structured Thinking to
resolve cross-category overlaps:

1. Call `mcp__structured-thinking__clear_thinking_history` to reset state
2. For each of the three agents' findings, call
   `mcp__structured-thinking__capture_thought` with a distinct `branch_id`
   per agent (e.g., "bloaters-dispensables", "couplers-oo-abusers",
   "change-preventers")
3. For each Critical finding, call
   `mcp__structured-thinking__retrieve_relevant_thoughts` to check whether
   other agents found supporting or conflicting evidence for the same
   underlying issue
4. Where two agents report the same issue at different severities, use
   `mcp__structured-thinking__revise_thought` to collapse to the more
   conservative rating
5. Call `mcp__structured-thinking__get_thinking_summary` to produce the
   collapsed view

Proceed to write the merged report from the summary. The Structured Thinking
output is an internal reasoning artifact — it does not appear in the final
report.

**Fallback:** If the Structured Thinking MCP is unavailable, stop and notify
the user. The synthesis step requires this tool for reliable cross-category
deduplication.

After all three agents return, merge their findings into a single report. Deduplicate
findings that multiple agents independently identified — keep the version with stronger
evidence and note which agents both flagged it.

Output format:

```
## Code Review: `<scope-path>`

**Smell Density: [Low | Moderate | Significant | High]**

Agents: Bloaters & Dispensables, Couplers & OO Abusers, Change Preventers.
Scope: `<scope-path>` (<file count> files, <languages>)

### Findings
- **Critical** | `file:line` | finding | evidence | smell: [category] | source: [agent(s)]
- **Serious** | `file:line` | finding | evidence | smell: [category] | source: [agent(s)]
- **Minor** | `file:line` | finding | evidence | smell: [category] | source: [agent(s)]

### Risk Rationale
- rationale statement
- rationale statement
- rationale statement
```

**Smell density criteria:**

The density level reflects how findings interact, not just their count.

- **Low** — Findings are independent and minor. The code is clean for its age and complexity.
- **Moderate** — Some findings share boundaries. Individual fixes are straightforward but
  a few areas deserve attention.
- **Significant** — Findings reinforce each other across multiple areas. Complexity and
  coupling are compounding. Coordinated refactoring needed.
- **High** — Findings are systemic with shared root causes. The code's structure actively
  resists change and will degrade further without intervention.

Omit empty sections. If there are no findings, say so plainly.

### Step 4 — Stop

The report is the deliverable. Do not modify code, create branches, or take further action
unless the user asks. The user decides how to respond to the findings.

## Boundaries

- This skill reviews existing code. For reviewing plans, use `chester-plan-smell`.
- This skill does not write or modify code. All output is inline in the conversation.
- This skill requires a scope. It will not review the entire repo by default.
- Each finding must have file-level evidence with line numbers. Drop any finding that
  cannot cite a real file and location. This is the single most important rule.
